@article{Motten1981,
abstract = {The pollination effectiveness and visitation rates of major insect visitors of Claytonia virginica, an obligately insect-pollinated spring wildflower, were measured in a North Carolina deciduous forest. Seed set in the population was not pollinator-limited except during rainy weather and very early in the flowering season. The solitary bee Andrena erigeniae and the beef fly Bombylius major were responsible for more than 75{\%} of the visits to C. virginica. A. erigeniae is a specialist on C. virginica, B. major is a common visitor to many plant species. The effectiveness of a pollinator was measured by the probability that a visit resulted in fruit (capsule) formation. For those flowers that were successfully pollinated and produced a capsule, number of seeds did not vary with visitor identity or the total number of visits received. Although B. major and female A. erigeniae differ greatly in morphology and foraging behavior, a visit by either insect results in equally high seed set. As B. major is about 2/3 as abundant as A. erigeniae females on C. virginica, both insects contribute substantially to seed set in the population. With the measured visitation frequency and pollination effectiveness, the generalist B. major alone has the potential to pollinate 3/4 of the flowers.},
